# C/C++ instructions

C/C++-specific rules for this project. Load these *in addition to*
the general instructions in `../general/`. The C++ file wins for C/C++
code where the two might disagree.

| File | When to load |
| --- | --- |
| `style.md` | Always when writing C++. Naming, formatting, headers, modules. |
| `tooling.md` | Whenever you touch the build, deps, or run a command. CMake, package manager, sanitisers. |
| `design.md` | Whenever you model a new type or interface. RAII, value semantics, ownership, concepts. |
| `patterns.md` | When you reach for a C++ pattern — PIMPL, NVI, CRTP-or-concept, type erasure, strong typedef. |
| `code-smells.md` | When you spot — or are about to write — common C++ anti-patterns (raw `new`, leaky casts, etc.). |
| `testing.md` | Whenever you write or run C++ tests. GoogleTest / Catch2, sanitisers, property-based. |

## Reading order

1. `style.md` (the baseline).
2. `tooling.md` (so you can build).
3. `design.md` and `patterns.md` (the modelling toolbox).
4. `code-smells.md` (what to refactor against).
5. `testing.md` (the test discipline).

## External authorities

- [C++ Core Guidelines](https://isocpp.github.io/CppCoreGuidelines/CppCoreGuidelines)
  (Bjarne Stroustrup & Herb Sutter) — the canonical reference. When in
  doubt, read the relevant rule there.
- [Google C++ Style Guide](https://google.github.io/styleguide/cppguide.html)
  — baseline style.
- *Effective Modern C++* (Scott Meyers) — the modern-features bible.
- *Tour of C++* (Stroustrup) — concise language tour.
- [LearnCpp](https://www.learncpp.com/) — well-written introductory
  material that stays current with modern C++.
